Air Pollution-Related Mortality and Income

Author

Flavia Marsico

1 Introduction

In 2020, The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME), in its Global Burden of Disease study, provided estimates of the number of deaths attributed to a range of risk factors for disease.The study determined that air pollution- the combination of outdoor and indoor particulate matter and ozone- is one of the leading risk factors for death and one of the worldâs largest health and environmental issues.In particular,in low-income countries, air pollution is often very near the top of the list or even the leading risk factor.This memo aims to provide a comprehensive report on the change in air pollution related mortality over time and show how air pollution differently affects countries according to their net national income

2 Data

In order to show how air pollution affects mortality around the world, I use data on the share of deaths attributed to air pollution from 1980 until 2019 from Our World in Data.To mitigate the influence of external factors such as the COVID-19 pandemic, which significantly altered air pollution levels due to widespread lockdown measures, I chose to use data only up to 2019. Similarly, to plot air pollution related mortality over time, I use data on the estimated annual number of deaths attributed to air pollution per 100,000 people. To analyze the relationship between air pollution related mortality and income, I use data from the World Bank on net national income per capita for all countries in the world.Finally, in order to visualize the share of deaths attributed to air pollution for each country in the world I use a shapefile of world polygons.

3 Maps for the Whole World

First, I create a Cloropleth map of the world using the wolrd shapefile to visualize the share of deaths attributed to air pollution in 2019.

From this map it is possible to look at the countries with the highest and lowest share of deaths attributed to air pollution. The minimum values are around 5% and below whereas the highest reach around 20% in 2019. Letâs compare this map with 1990.

In 1990 the share of deaths attributed to air pollution was higher with values reaching up to 25% and slightly above.Looking at this map, one of the countries that stands out for its high percentage share is China.

Letâs take a closer look at how Chinaâs share of deaths attributed to air pollution has changed from 1990 until 2019.

4 Map China 1990 vs 2019

  • China 1990 vs China 2019

By looking at these two images, we notice that the share of deaths attributed to air pollution in china has decreased, although not extremely significantly.Similarly, countries such as the United States and Russia show a decreasing trend in deaths attributed to air pollution over time.

In order to have a more precise and clear representation of how the share of deaths by air pollution has changed over time, I use a time trend plot with data on the estimated annual number of deaths attributed to air pollution per 100,000 people.

5 Time Trend

Vizualizing the time trend we clearly notice a steady decrease in the number of deaths atributed to air pollution from 1990 until 2019.According to a research conducted by Our Wolrd in Data,this decline has been primarily driven by improvements in indoor air pollution rather than outdoor. The latter has indeed decreased more modestly.

After determining that air pollution related mortality has decreased over time, I use a barplot that relates the estimated annual number of deaths attributed to air pollution per 100,000 people to the Net National Income per capita of each country in the world.After subsetting each country into high, middle or low income group I plot the data to highlight where most of the deaths attributed to air pollution occur.

6 Income and Air Pollution Mortality

Income Plot Air Pollution Mortality

The barplot shows that the number of deaths is quite significantly higher in low income countries, followed by middle income countries and lastly high income countries.According to Our Wolrd In Data, the burden of air pollution tends to be greater across both low and middle-income countries for two reasons: indoor pollution rates tend to be high in low-income countries due to a reliance on solid fuels for cooking, and outdoor air pollution tends to increase as countries industrialize and shift from low to middle incomes.

6.1 Income and Air Pollution Mortality Time Animation

Finally, to have have a more detailed grasp on how income actually affects air pollution related mortality, I use an animated plot as displayed below.

This plot shows how air pollution related mortality fluctuates based on the level of income.Where the values of net national income per capita are lower, closer to the zero, deaths are significantly more numerous. On the contrary, where the values of net national income per capita increase, deaths remain low, as displayed towards the end of the plot.

7 Conclusion

  • This memo has provided a comprehensive overview of how air pollution related mortality has changed over time.Over the past few decades, there has been a notable decline in air pollution-related mortality globally. While this decline is encouraging, it is important to note that improvements have been more pronounced in indoor air pollution compared to outdoor air pollution.
  • Despite overall improvements, disparities persist across countries, with low and middle-income countries bearing a disproportionate burden of air pollution-related deaths. This is attributed to factors such as reliance on solid fuels for cooking in low-income countries and increased outdoor air pollution in middle-income countries undergoing industrialization.
  • The analysis further highlights the strong correlation between national income levels and air pollution-related mortality. Low-income countries tend to experience significantly higher mortality rates compared to middle and high-income countries.
  • These findings underscore the importance of targeted interventions to address air pollution-related mortality, particularly in low and middle income countries. Policy measures aimed at reducing indoor air pollution, transitioning to cleaner energy sources, and improving outdoor air quality are crucial for mitigating the health impacts of air pollution and improving access to healthy lifestyles among countries.
